<h1>@HI{{dou}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N{{}}@HI{{@EM{{dou}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{dou}}}} is an interrogative adverb which is used to inquire about a state or a way of doing something..

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{o@KJ{{mother}}sanha@EM{{dou}}desuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      How is your mother?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{dou}}}} can be used to make an offer or make a suggestion. In this case @HI{{@EM{{dou}}}} is asking about the state of the listener's mnind.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{soil^weekday^day}}:doyoubi}}ha@EM{{dou}}?}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      How about Saturday?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{dou}}}} can be used to ask how to do something. @HI{{ikaga}} is not
normally used in this case.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kono@FG{{@KJ{{say^leaf}}:kotoba}}ha@EM{{dou}}@KJ{{read}}mimasuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      How do you read this word?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
The idiomatic expression @HI{{doushite}} is used to ask about manner, reason or causes. The reply should
normally end in @HI{{kara}} ("because").

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kono@KJ{{tree}}ha@EM{{dou}}shite@FG{{@KJ{{wither}}:ka}}retandesuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Why did this tree die?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@HI{{ikaga}} is the polite version of @HI{{@EM{{dou}}}} .
</p>

